## 5. React & Next.js Patterns

### Components

- Default to Server Components. Only use `"use client"` when absolutely necessary (interactivity, browser APIs, hooks).
- Keep `"use client"` components as small as possible — push them to the leaves of the component tree.
- Never fetch data inside Client Components — fetch in Server Components and pass as props.
- Use `React.FC` sparingly; prefer plain function declarations with explicit return types.

```tsx
// ✅ Good - Server Component
async function UserPage({ params }: { params: { id: string } }) {
  const user = await getUserById(params.id);
  return <UserCard user={user} />;
}

// ❌ Bad - useEffect data fetching
useEffect(() => { fetch('/api/user').then(...) }, []);
```

### Server Actions

- All mutations go through Server Actions in `/actions/`.
- Always validate inputs with Zod inside the action.
- Return a typed response object; never throw to the client.

```ts
// actions/create-user.action.ts
"use server";
import { createUserSchema } from "@/schemas/user.schema";

export async function createUser(formData: FormData) {
  const parsed = createUserSchema.safeParse(Object.fromEntries(formData));
  if (!parsed.success) {
    return { success: false, errors: parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
  }
  // ...db logic
  return { success: true };
}
```

### Data Fetching

- Fetch data in Server Components using `async/await` directly.
- Use `cache()` from React or `unstable_cache` from Next.js for expensive queries.
- Colocate data fetching with the component that needs it.

